          <h2
            style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.5;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            "
          >
            Army Sergeant opens fire
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>
              Summary: Logistics sergeant’s alleged shooting leaves fellow
              soldiers wounded, expected to face prison time.
            </strong>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Sgt. Quornelius Radford, a 28-year-old Army logistics specialist
            from Jacksonville, Florida, is
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-7-aug-25-spotlight-h3-10-accused-of-opening-fire?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >accused of opening fire</a
            >
            on five co-workers inside Fort Stewart, Georgia. The attack occurred
            at his duty station using a personal handgun, not a military-issued
            weapon. Fellow soldiers tackled and subdued Radford before law
            enforcement arrived. While all victims are expected to recover, two
            sustained serious injuries.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Radford, who has no known deployment history and no formal
            disciplinary record, had recently been arrested for DUI, an incident
            his command was unaware of. Authorities will investigate his motive
            and determine how he smuggled the weapon onto the base. He is
            expected to face a general court-martial and will face confinement
            in a military prison.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            President Trump addressed the incident from the Oval Office. He
            called it an “<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #4d3060;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.presidentialsummary.com/ps-7-aug-25-spotlight-h3-11-atrocity?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >atrocity</a
            >” and vowed prosecution to the fullest extent of the law. He also
            prayed for the victims and emphasized national unity in supporting
            soldiers and their families. The Secretary of Defense praised law
            enforcement for its swift response and stated that justice would be
            brought to Radford and any potential co-conspirators, although no
            accomplices have been reported.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
